As Jaymes wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/20/2004 at 10:56:01 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Just wondering if this will be my claim to fame, or if this has 
>already been observed:
>
>I was looking at the first several perfect numbers (6, 28, 496, 
>8128, 33550336, 8589869056, 137438691328, 2305843008139952128) and 
>noticed, except for 6, that if you add the digits together and then 
>add the digits of that result and repeat, you're eventually left 
>with 1.  Example:  1+3+7+4+3+8+6+9+1+3+2+8 = 55; 5+5 = 10; 1+0 = 1.
>
>[Difficulty]
>Nothing really confusing.
>
>[Thoughts]
>Has this already been recorded and given some fancy name?

Hi,

Thanks for writing to Dr. Math.

You are talking about the "digital root" of perfect numbers, or
"additive persistence". It is known that the digital root of all even
perfect numbers (except for 6) is 1. 

I hope this helps, and keep looking for interesting facts about numbers.

- Doctor Roy, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

